<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-774-398  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 774 398.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX World  August 1990 v7 n8 p71(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>In search of text. (text retrieval systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Baldwin, Howard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The decreasing cost of disk space and the proliferation ofmachine-readable information has triggered an explosion in theranks of text retrieval systems.andP;  The UNIX segment is currentlycomprised of nine products, half of them under one year old.andP;  Textretrieval systems access information through the use of Booleanlogic, using and, or, and not conditions to search forinformation.andP;  Some packages also offer commands that allowsearching for keywords adjacent to or within certain proximity toother keywords.andP;  Still other packages are only marginally based onthe Boolean system, using instead search strategies that allow forless specificity and a broader sweep of available information.andO;Some of the text retrieval systems entering the UNIX environmentoffer special features under UNIX not available in the proprietaryversions of the packages.andP;  For example, by Thunderstone'sMetamorph and Third Eye's Elexir allow searching information fromlive data feeds under UNIX.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Future of ComputingUNIXText Data BasesInformation Storage and RetrievalBoolean Algebra.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   For more information. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>